      "Times were different in the 70s.. girls stripped to marching band music and guys who looked like the therapist from M*A*S*H are suave ladies-man detectives.  What a wild time.  Anyway, this had a little bit more story than the last H.G. Lewis movie I watched, <strong>The Wizard of Gore</strong>.  Oddly enough, this is fourth whodunit murder mystery in a row in this watchlist with a reveal at the end.  I expected it of the slashers and the giallos, sure, but not so much Universal and H.G. Lewis.  The gore here is about what I’ve come to expect with these movies, although it seems like there is a little bit less of it this time.  The tone is pretty goofy and there are about a million times a woman walks into a room where another had just been killed and then screams when she sees what happened.  It gets pretty ridiculous.  The main guy is overly cool and calm, maybe he is supposed to be a parody.  Anyway, I doubt people watch it for the characters and story, so if you want gross kills and some nudity, it’s there, waiting for you.  Not really a good movie but it’s a little bit fun.",
