      "Onto a new theme: non-horror movies based on Stephen King stories.  Some of my favorite movies of all time fall under this category. <strong>Stand By Me (1986)</strong>, <strong>The Shawshank Redemption (1994)</strong>, and <strong>The Green Mile (1999)</strong>.  Of course, I like a lot of the horror movies made based on his work, but with horror in general, the quality is pretty hit-or-miss.  Anyway, I have a lot of (almost all of?  Minus sequels, etc) Stephen King movies on blu-ray, DVD and VHS, but I could only find three that I hadn’t seen that looked like they weren’t really horror at all and Dolores Claiborne is the earliest of those.  This is one that has no supernatural element at all.. it’s just a straight drama about a older mother accused of killing a woman for whom she had been a live-in caregiver (hey I used ‘whom’ correctly I think) and her adult journalist daughter who comes back home to find out what happened and try to help her out against the investigators.  It’s not too complicated but still ends up over 2 hours long, but that’s mostly because there are several flashbacks.  In the end, it’s pretty good if a bit slow sometimes.  The cast is the main reason I enjoyed it, especially Kathy Bates.  And of course, Mainer accents.  It’s a good movie if you like family drama.",
